The '''post-Napoleonic depression''' was an [[depression (economics)|economic depression]] in Europe after the end of the [[Napoleonic wars]].

In [[England]], an agricultural depression led to the passage of the [[Corn Laws]] (which were to polarize British politics for the next three decades), and placed great strain on the system of [[English Poor Laws|poor relief inherited from Elizabethan times]].<ref>Lord Ernle, ''English Farming Past and Present''. Fifth Edition. (London: Longmans, Green & Co., Ltd. 1936), [http://www.soilandhealth.org/01aglibrary/010136ernle/010136ch15.htm Chapter XV: Agricultural Depression and the Poor Law 1813-37]</ref>

Also, after the end of the [[Napoleonic Wars]] in 1815, a brief boom in [[Textile manufacture during the Industrial Revolution|textile manufacture]] in England was followed by periods of chronic industrial economic depression, particularly among textile weavers and spinners (the textile trade was concentrated in Lancashire).<ref>*{{citation |last=Frangopulo |first=N. J. |year=1977 |title=Tradition in Action: The Historical Evolution of the Greater Manchester County |publisher=EP Publishing |isbn=978-0-7158-1203-7|page=30}}</ref> Weavers who could have expected to earn 15&nbsp;shillings for a six-day week in 1803, saw their wages cut to 5&nbsp;shillings or even 4s&nbsp;6[[British one penny coin (pre-decimal)|d]] by 1818.<ref name="hernon22">{{citation |first=Ian |last=Hernon |year=2006 |title=Riot!: Civil Insurrection from Peterloo to the Present Day |publisher=Pluto Press |isbn=978-0-7453-2538-5 |page=22}}</ref> The industrialists, who were cutting wages without offering relief, blamed market forces generated by the aftershocks of the Napoleonic Wars.<ref name="hernon22"/>

At the same time, the [[Corn Laws]] (the first of which was passed in 1815) exacerbated the situation. They imposed a [[tariff]] on foreign grain in an effort to [[Protectionism|protect]] English grain producers (agricultural landowners). The cost of food for working people rose as people were forced to buy the more expensive and lower quality British grain, and periods of famine and chronic unemployment ensued, increasing the desire for political reform both in Lancashire and in the country at large.<ref name="County of Lancs: Manchester">{{cite book |author=Farrer, William |author2=Brownbill, John |title=The Victoria history of the county of Lancaster. – Lancashire. Vol.4 |chapter= The city and parish of Manchester: Introduction |origyear=1911 |chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41404 |accessdate= 27 March 2008 |year=2003–2006 |publisher=University of London & History of Parliament Trust }}</ref><ref>*{{citation |last=Glen |first=Robert |title=Urban workers in the early Industrial Revolution |year=1984 |publisher=Croom Helm |isbn=0-7099-1103-3 |pages=194–252}}</ref>

In [[Scotland]], the depression ended in 1822.<ref name="Saville1996">{{cite book|author=Richard Saville|title=Bank of Scotland: a history, 1695-1995|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=USQkqlHTfnAC&pg=PA484|accessdate=9 March 2011|year=1996|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-0-7486-0757-0|page=484}}</ref>

Samuel Jackson of Pennsylvania theorised that the [[Panic of 1819]] and resulting depression in the United States were caused by the post-Napoleonic depression, holding that the end of the Napoleonic wars had led to the collapse of export markets and resulting [[underconsumption]].<ref>Murray N. Rothbard, ''The Panic Of 1819: Reactions and Policies'', p.213</ref>

